The strike affected the only weekly flight from Lilongwe (through Blantyre) to Johannesburg, South Africa, according to local media. Stranded passengers turned up at the Kamuzu International Airport to find grounded planes. The airline crew and staff stormed the companyâ€™s head office in Lilongwe demanding answers from the management, local media reported. The salary deductions were made without prior notice or consultations, according to the staff. The airline was grounded in March because of coronavirus. It resumed flights in October. Malawi Airlines is owned by the government with Ethiopian Airlines having some shares, according to Malawi 24. --BBC--